  "footnotes": [
    "West / Oran: dominated by the Mauretanian and later Zayyanid/Abdalwadid dynasty (Tlemcen, 1235–1556), a major Berber state; Spain occupied Oran twice (1509–1708, 1732–1792); the Emir Abdelkader (1832–1847) waged the first major war of resistance against French colonialism from this region",
    "Algiers / Center: site of ancient Ikosim; the Ottoman Regency of Algiers (1516–1830) made Algiers one of the most powerful naval states in the Mediterranean — the Barbary pirates operated from here; French conquest began with the 1830 landing at Sidi Ferruch",
    "Kabylia: the mountainous highland east of Algiers; the Kuku Kingdom and Aït Abbas Emirate maintained independence from the Ottoman Regency throughout the 16th–19th centuries; Kabyle resistance to French rule lasted until 1872; the region remains culturally Berber (Amazigh)",
    "East / Constantine: the ancient Numidian heartland (Cirta/Constantine); Jugurtha's resistance against Rome (111–105 BCE) was centered here; under the Hafsid dynasty before Ottoman conquest; the Tuggurt Sultanate in the eastern Sahara maintained autonomy until 1854",
    "Rustamid dynasty (777–909, Tiaret): the only Ibadi (Kharijite) state in the Maghreb; founded by Abd al-Rahman ibn Rustam; controlled trans-Saharan trade; destroyed by the Fatimid invasion of 909 CE",
    "Hammadid dynasty (1014–1152): founded by Hammad ibn Buluggin, nephew of the Zirid founder; built the spectacular palace-city of Qal'at Banu Hammad (now a UNESCO site); nominally Sunni and hostile to Fatimid Ismaili doctrine",
    "Algerian Civil War / Black Decade (1991–2002): after the military cancelled elections that the Islamic Salvation Front (FIS) was set to win, the Armed Islamic Group (GIA) launched a brutal insurgency; an estimated 150,000–200,000 killed; effectively ended with the 2002 Civil Concord"
  ]
